<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_theory" title=3D=
"Probability theory">probability theory</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statistics">statistics</a>, the <b>expon=
ential distribution</b> or <b>negative exponential distribution</b> is the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distribution" title=3D=
"Probability distribution">probability distribution</a> of the distance bet=
ween events in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_point_pro=
cess" title=3D"Poisson point process">Poisson point process</a>, i.e., a pr=
ocess in which events occur continuously and independently at a constant av=
erage rate; the distance parameter could be any meaningful mono-dimensional=
 measure of the process, such as time between production errors, or length =
along a roll of fabric in the weaving manufacturing process.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expone=
ntial_distribution#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is a particular case of the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gamma_distribution" title=3D"Gamma =
distribution">gamma distribution</a>. It is the continuous analogue of the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_distribution" title=3D"G=
eometric distribution">geometric distribution</a>, and it has the key prope=
rty of being <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Memoryless" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Memoryless">memoryless</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_distr=
ibution#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In addition to being used for the analysis =
of Poisson point processes it is found in various other contexts.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-Weisstein_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Exponential_distribution#cite_note-Weisstein-3"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The exponential distribution is not the same as the class of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_families" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Exponential families">exponential families</a> of distributions=
. This is a large class of probability distributions that includes the expo=
nential distribution as one of its members, but also includes many other di=
stributions, like the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distr=
ibution" title=3D"Normal distribution">normal</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_distribution" title=3D"Binomial distribution">bin=
omial</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gamma_distribution" tit=
le=3D"Gamma distribution">gamma</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
