        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">[</mo>
        <mi>X</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">]</mo>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mn>1</mn>
            <mi>=CE=BB<!-- =CE=BB --></mi>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \operatorname=
 {E} [X]=3D{\frac {1}{\lambda }}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/f9efa3ce3c964c59532609b3d6b8f01ce88f6221" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -2.005ex; width:10.793ex; height:5.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \=
operatorname {E} [X]=3D{\frac {1}{\lambda }}.}"></span>
</p><p>In light of the examples given <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Exponential_distribution#Occurrence_and_applications">below</a>, this m=
akes sense; a person who receives an average of two telephone calls per hou=
r can expect that the time between consecutive calls will be 0.5 hour, or 3=
0 minutes.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variance" title=3D"Vari=
ance">variance</a> of <i>X</i> is given by
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle \operatorname {Var} [X]=3D{\frac {1}{\lambda ^{2}}},}">
