span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_distrib=
ution#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Perfectly calibrated probabilities have the=
 property that the predicted probabilities match the frequency of out-of-sa=
mple events exactly. For the exponential, there is an exact expression for =
Bayesian predictions generated using the Haar prior, given by
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><=
math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle=
 p_{\rm {Haar-prior}}(x_{n+1}\mid x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n})=3D{\frac {n^{n+1}\le=
ft({\overline {x}}\right)^{n}}{\left(n{\overline {x}}+x_{n+1}\right)^{n+1}}=
}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
