-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -3.171ex; margin-left: -0.089ex; width:48.317ex; height:7.176ex;" a=
lt=3D"{\displaystyle p_{\rm {Haar-prior}}(x_{n+1}\mid x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n})=
=3D{\frac {n^{n+1}\left({\overline {x}}\right)^{n}}{\left(n{\overline {x}}+=
x_{n+1}\right)^{n+1}}}.}"></span>
</p><p>This is an example of calibrating prior prediction, in which the pri=
or is chosen to improve calibration (and, in this case, to make the calibra=
tion perfect). Calibrating prior prediction for the exponential using the H=
aar prior is implemented in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R_=
(programming_language)" title=3D"R (programming language)">R</a> software p=
ackage fitdistcp.<a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external autonumber" href=3D"=
https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/fitdistcp/index.html">[1]</a>
</p><p>The same prediction can be derived from a number of other perspectiv=
es, as discussed in the <a class=3D"mw-selflink-fragment" href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_distribution#Prediction">prediction</a> se=
ction below.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Occurrence_and_applications=
">Occurrence and applications</h2></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Occurrence_of_events">Occur=
rence of events</h3></div>
<p>The exponential distribution occurs naturally when describing the length=
s of the inter-arrival times in a homogeneous <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Poisson_process" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Poisson process=
">Poisson process</a>.
</p><p>The exponential distribution may be viewed as a continuous counterpa=
rt of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_distribution" =
title=3D"Geometric distribution">geometric distribution</a>, which describe=
s the number of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernoulli_trial" t=
itle=3D"Bernoulli trial">Bernoulli trials</a> necessary for a <i>discrete</=
i> process to change state. In contrast, the exponential distribution descr=
ibes the time for a continuous process to change state.
</p><p>In real-world scenarios, the assumption of a constant rate (or proba=
bility per unit time) is rarely satisfied. For example, the rate of incomin=
g phone calls differs according to the time of day. But if we focus on a ti=
me interval during which the rate is roughly constant, such as from 2 to 4 =
p.m. during work days, the exponential distribution can be used as a good a=
pproximate model for the time until the next phone call arrives. Similar ca=
veats apply to the following examples which yield approximately exponential=
ly distributed variables:
</p>
<ul><li>The time until a radioactive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Particle_decay" title=3D"Particle decay">particle decays</a>, or the tim=
e between clicks of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geiger_count=
er" title=3D"Geiger counter">Geiger counter</a></li>
<li>The time between receiving one telephone call and the next</li>
<li>The time until default (on payment to company debt holders) in reduced-=
form credit risk modeling</li></ul>
<p>Exponential variables can also be used to model situations where certain=
 events occur with a constant probability per unit length, such as the dist=
ance between <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mutation" title=3D"Mu=
tation">mutations</a> on a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DNA" ti=
tle=3D"DNA">DNA</a> strand, or between <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Roadkill" title=3D"Roadkill">roadkills</a> on a given road.
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queuing_theory" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Queuing theory">queuing theory</a>, the service time=
s of agents in a system (e.g. how long it takes for a bank teller etc. to s=
erve a customer) are often modeled as exponentially distributed variables. =
 (The arrival of customers for instance is also modeled by the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_distribution" title=3D"Poisson distrib=
ution">Poisson distribution</a> if the arrivals are independent and distrib=
uted identically.)  The length of a process that can be thought of as a seq=
uence of several independent tasks follows the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Erlang_distribution" title=3D"Erlang distribution">Erlang dist=
ribution</a> (which is the distribution of the sum of several independent e=
xponentially distributed variables).
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reliability_theory" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Reliability theory">Reliability theory</a> and <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reliability_engineering" title=3D"Re=
liability engineering">reliability engineering</a> also make extensive use =
of the exponential distribution. Because of the memoryless property of this=
 distribution, it is well-suited to model the constant <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hazard_rate" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hazard rat=
e">hazard rate</a> portion of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Bathtub_curve" title=3D"Bathtub curve">bathtub curve</a> used in reliabilit=
y theory. It is also very convenient because it is so easy to add <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Failure_rate" title=3D"Failure rate">fail=
ure rates</a> in a reliability model. The exponential distribution is howev=
er not appropriate to model the overall lifetime of organisms or technical =
devices, because the "failure rates" here are not constant: more failures o=
ccur for very young and for very old systems.
</p>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:FitExponDistr.tif" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://up=
load.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e4/FitExponDistr.tif/lossless-=
page1-260px-FitExponDistr.tif.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"260" height=
=3D"194" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"623" data-file-height=
=3D"465"></a><figcaption>Fitted cumulative exponential distribution to annu=
ally maximum 1-day rainfalls</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">p=
hysics</a>, if you observe a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gas" =
title=3D"Gas">gas</a> at a fixed <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T=
emperature" title=3D"Temperature">temperature</a> and <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pressure" title=3D"Pressure">pressure</a> in a uniform =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gravitational_field" title=3D"Grav=
itational field">gravitational field</a>, the heights of the various molecu=
les also follow an approximate exponential distribution, known as the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barometric_formula" title=3D"Barometric=
 formula">Barometric formula</a>. This is a consequence of the entropy prop=
erty mentioned below.
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrology" title=3D"Hydr=
ology">hydrology</a>, the exponential distribution is used to analyze extre=
me values of such variables as monthly and annual maximum values of daily r=
ainfall and river discharge volumes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_distribution#cite=
_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd>The blue picture illustrates an example of fitting the exponential =
distribution to ranked annually maximum one-day rainfalls showing also the =
90% <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_belt" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Confidence belt">confidence belt</a> based on the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_distribution" title=3D"Binomial =
distribution">binomial distribution</a>. The rainfall data are represented =
by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plotting_position" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Plotting position">plotting positions</a> as part of the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cumulative_frequency_analysis" ti=
tle=3D"Cumulative frequency analysis">cumulative frequency analysis</a>.</d=
d></dl>
<p>In operating-rooms management, the distribution of surgery duration for =
a category of surgeries with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Predi=
ctive_methods_for_surgery_duration" title=3D"Predictive methods for surgery=
 duration">no typical work-content</a> (like in an emergency room, encompas=
sing all types of surgeries).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Prediction">Prediction</h3>=
</div>
<p>Having observed a sample of <i>n</i> data points from an unknown exponen=
tial distribution a common task is to use these samples to make predictions=
 about future data from the same source. A common predictive distribution o=
ver future samples is the so-called plug-in distribution, formed by pluggin=
g a suitable estimate for the rate parameter <i>=CE=BB</i> into the exponen=
tial density function. A common choice of estimate is the one provided by t=
he principle of maximum likelihood, and using this yields the predictive de=
nsity over a future sample <i>x</i><sub><i>n</i>+1</sub>, conditioned on th=
e observed samples <i>x</i> =3D (<i>x</i><sub>1</sub>, ..., <i>x<sub>n</sub=
></i>) given by
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
