an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>the Conditional Normalized Maximum Likelihood (CNML) predictive distrib=
ution, from information theoretic considerations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_dist=
ribution#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ol>
<p>The accuracy of a predictive distribution may be measured using the dist=
ance or divergence between the true exponential distribution with rate para=
meter, <i>=CE=BB</i><sub>0</sub>, and the predictive distribution based on =
the sample <i>x</i>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kullback%=
E2%80%93Leibler_divergence" title=3D"Kullback=E2=80=93Leibler divergence">K=
ullback=E2=80=93Leibler divergence</a> is a commonly used, parameterisation=
 free measure of the difference between two distributions. Letting =CE=94(<=
i>=CE=BB</i><sub>0</sub>||<i>p</i>) denote the Kullback=E2=80=93Leibler div=
ergence between an exponential with rate parameter <i>=CE=BB</i><sub>0</sub=
> and a predictive distribution <i>p</i> it can be shown that
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
